messages: A bag I fill, yet I weigh nothing, what am I?
A bird is built without me. I have to be broken to let water out. What am I?

A bird is in a box with only two holes. One hole is big enough for the bird to fly out but not big enough for the bird to fly in. The other hole is big enough for the bird to fly in but not big enough for the bird to fly out. How did the bird get into the box?
A bird is in a cage without wings. How did it get there?
A bird is in a cage. The cage is hanging by a thread. The thread is held by a man. The man is standing on a bridge over a river. If the bridge collapses, will the birdfly away?
A bird is sitting in a tree, has only to spread its wings to be twice as big. What bird is that?
A bird so small it fits in the palm of your hand, But in the vast desert, it makes a mighty band.
A bird that sings at dawn, yet is not a nightingale. What bird is this?
A bird with a broken wing, I cannot fly. I am baked, but I am not bread. What am I?
A bird’s delight, in the trees that it builds, from my branches, I bring forth tales that are wild and beguiled.
A box I am with a lock so tight, I hold a secret, a treasure out of sight.
A box I store, but not what I store. I'm often locked with gold or ore.
A box full of holes. It still holds water, but none can touch or drink.
A box held in hand, always feels light, Yet the heaviest thing in sight.
A box of matches, a lighted match, what's the final flare that catches?
A box so light it weighs nothing, yet holds the whole world within.
A box that's filled with sand, yet is lighter than a grain.
A box with eight sides, it has but one entrance, it starts off big and ends as nothing, what am I?
A box with holes but never opens, speaks but makes no sound. What is it?
A box without hinges, key, or lid, yet golden treasure inside is hid.
A bus full of lawyers went off a cliff. How many lawyers were on the bus, but survived?
A city with five gates, guarded by a lion, a tiger, a monkey, and a bear. No one who enters the gate can come back. What city is this?
A city's biggest resident is not human, what is it?
A color I am not, but I make a picture bright, I'm invisible in the dark, but I give off light.
A color that is not black, but is related to it. If you add white, it becomes another color. What am I?
A color we can see, but not feel or taste, that makes the sun set. What am I?
A constant companion, shapeless, weightless, it's written in every book, it's present in every place you look, what is it?
A container so simple, Holding a meal or a meal, With many uses, yet not edible, What am I?
A container that you fill with water at the top, and children play with the bottom.
A continuous line with no beginning or end, I'm bent but never broken, and I join things together. What am I?
A continuous line without a beginning or an end. What am I?

A creature of the earth, living under ground, sometimes it's found in a dungeon, sometimes in a mound. It's not an animal, nor a plant, but it does change form when it's brought to the light. What am I?
A creature sleeps in a dark, silent pond. Stirred, it brings forth a sound, what am I?
A creature that can live a thousand years, but cannot live for a day without me. What is it?
A creature that does not bark, yet guards its home with might, It's size can vary, day or night.
A creature that does not exist on land or sea. It screams as it's born, but dies the moment it's free.
A creature that goes around but never moves. It has a head, shoulders, arms, and legs, but it does not walk. What is it?
A creature that grows as it goes, which takes less space the more it grows. What am I?
A creature that is born at midnight, grows up in the day, is fed in the evening, and is taken to the market in the morning. What is it?
A creature that is born with its eyes open, yet cannot see. What is it?
A creature that is not a bird, but can fly above the earth. What am I?
A creature that is not alive, yet is taken for a ride. It is carried on the back of a man, and when it reaches the head, it can no longer hide.
A creature that lives in the desert and smells like a dead rat, it has no mouth, no nose, no eyes, no legs, no neck, but it can kill you with a single touch.
A creature that moves at night, turns silver in the light, changes shape to avoid the sight, what am I?
A creature that moves in the evening, with a voice like the howling of wolves. It has a body that gleams in the moonlight, but it is not a beast.
A creature that roams at night, with a cry that pierces the stillness of the dark.
A creature that roars in the depths, ancient and fierce, its power unmatched, its presence dire. With scales that shine like the night, and eyes that burn with an eerie light.
A creature that roars when it's born, and weeps when it's died, when I'm young I'm called a lamb, but when old, I'm called a ram.
A creature that speaks without a mouth and has no need for food. It can travel any distance without moving its feet.
A creature that walks on four legs in the morning, two legs at noon, and three legs in the evening. What is it?
A creature that walks on its hands at night and on its feet in the day. What is it?
A creature that's always hungry, its voice a mournful sound, Eats nothing but the stars at night, yet always goes around.
A creature that's big, a creature that's small, a creature that's tall, none of them have any bones at all.
A creature that's born asleep, and stays asleep till it dies.
A creature that's born at night but is not bat. It brings us light, yet it hurts our eyes. What am I?
A creature that's born at noon and dies at sunset. What am I?
A creature that's born at noon, thrives in the cold, in a drink that's white and blue, I'm older than the universe, yet some of my kind may end me. Tell me, what am I?
A creature that's born in darkness and dies in darkness, and in between it eats, usually in pairs. What is it?
A creature that's both fierce and shy, with a fur that's black as the night, it roams the forest, hunting its prey, the bells on its neck jingle as it plays its part in the ballet of the woods.
A creature that's got five toes, and when it's angry it turns red and grows.
A creature that's got ten toes and prefers the mud, when it's hot, it sheds its brood.
A creature that's light, yet heavy to hold, In stillness, it shines like pure gold.
A creature that's long and serpent-like, Often feared and misunderstood, It sheds its skin, yet it never tire or bask in the sun.
A creature that's not alive, but grows in the heart of a pine, what is it?
A creature that's often taken for a fool, With a head that bobs and a tail that's cool. Found in water, it's usually blue, In a bowl or a pond, it's me and you.
A creature which takes its form from water, but never gets wet. What am I?
A creature with a heart that doesn't beat, and it is often found in the deepest seas.
A creature with a heart that never beats, A voice without a tongue to speak, I live inside a world that's neat, Enclosed in shadows, I can never leak. What am I?
A creature with a thousand eyes, a legless form, it leaves no trace. What am I?
A creature with a thousand eyes, yet never closes them in sleep. What is it?
A creature with a voice so loud, it's heard around the world, but never speaks a word.
A creature with four wings and claws, A beast that roams both land and air, A symbol of fear and fire, A creature whose fate's undesire.
A creature with hands, but no fingers to count, A voice so sweet it will have you entranced, A presence so powerful, it leaves not a pound, What am I?
A creature with many faces, Changing forms, sometimes wondrous, Seen as a symbol of change, What am I?
A creature with neither bones nor marrow, and though its back be broken, it will not die. What is it?
A crystal castle, ever so grand, I cradle not water, but hold wind in my hand.
A day old.
A dodecahedron.
A father hits it, a son drives it, but what is it?
A fish has my power, a fowl has my secret, a serpent has my end. What am I?
A force of nature, the essence of emotion.
A four-letter word, it's short but it's strong, In winter, it's in the sky, but in the summer, it belongs.
A friend of mine is not alive, but I've carried it in my chest all of my life.
A friend to swimmers, not a friend to sailors, I make things shrink, but I'm not a jailer.
A frozen lake is its home, in winter it's a star, in summer it's a roaming nomad.
A giant's game requiring 20 points, you're sure to win unless it's fought. What is it?
A grain of rice in an empty pot, when tossed will never quit. What am I?
A grain of rice in my hand, if I double it daily, in one thousand days how much will I have?
A hand that holds a key opens it, but if it's empty, it still works the same way. What am I?
A hand that's always empty, a pocket that's never full. What am I?
A hollow, silent house, empty, save for the roar, the sea within, its waves endless, its power unyielding, a sound you can't ignore.
A joke.
A kind of box that is always empty. What am I?
A large container I carry, on my back and often my shoulder, holding food, water, or other things, what am I?
A large container holds a gallon and a half. What is it?
A large drink, carried in two hands. Can you tell me its name?
A large house with no doors or windows, where do I keep my corn?
A letter, silent, in a word you find, changing a story's final bind.
A light bulb works best in which numbered month?
A living creature with seven heads, Seven bodies beneath, One is born, one dies, while the others all feed.
A living thing that's born in Spring, grows all through the year, what lies quiet in the snow, yet makes the rivers flow?
A long sleep I give to him who is named after my father. In a silver shell I lie in my mother's home. With me, time flies, while all without me is a waste.
A long sleep I had, in an ivory tower. Awake I rose and from that hour, I was sought by many a power.
A long sleep I take every year, From autumn till spring I'm never clear. A wake I make that's loud and bright, then into slumber sinks out of sight.
A long sleep that I take, a wake I don't make. I'm frozen, yet I'm not cold, what am I?
A long sleep that a worker takes, a short sleep that a king takes, a propagation that makes a crowd. What am I?
A long sleep that is broken by a little noise.
A long sleep that's pleasant, a rest called vacation, a short sleep that's not sound, all share my name.
A long sleep, a long sleep, I take from thee, I give to thee on bended knee. Three score and ten I keep, a long sleep, a long sleep, I give. What is it?
A long time I ago I was taken, I was bound with my own tail, All day I am hungry, all night I'm chained, It's my own voice that keeps me wailing.
A long time I grew, in hiding far from sight, In darkness deep, I took my might, Now when I'm cut, I leak my light.
A long-legged bird is spotted on a branch. Which one is it?
A long-lived traveller, I go fast yet never reach my goal, I can't be touched or held, I can't be seen or caught. What am I?
A long-time friend who's always by my side, yet never speaks a word. What is it?
A man and his horse fell into a pit. The man was able to get out, but he couldn't help the horse. Why?
A man is Born at night, and yet he brings the light. What am I?
A man walks into a room. He is holding a lit match. Suddenly, the room fills with light, yet the man does not blow out the match. Why?
A maze in a box, no single maze's ways.
A means of transportation, for both rich and poor, pot and lot.
A mirror reflects what is real, but has no substance of its own.
A monster with six eyes, the last one is in the mouth, I kill with a single touch, what am I?
A monster with three heads I do meet, Two I can tame, but the third I can't Greets me at city's busy street. What should I do?
A mother looks in, but does not see. She touches me but does not feel. What am I?
A mother saw her child in distress, and she cried, "Oh, what a shame it is!" What was it?
A mother sees her child born, but never sees her daughter. Who is the mother?
A palindrome without vowels, often a source of great strife, remove two letters, what remains is still life.
A palindrome; read it backward, it’s a crime.
A part of life, a creature of the mind.
A person is born with it, but it cannot be bought; it cannot be stolen. What is it?
A person is born, gets married, has children, and then dies. But where does he go when he is not alive?
A place of many rooms, where you can add your own. When you lose your way and come back home, you'll find your thoughts are new.
A place that reveals what our hearts can be.
A powerful force that's always present, drawing near.
A pulse all steady, yet I'm not deceased.
A puzzle box holds my secrets, I'm opened by a cleverer wit.
A question I ask, but not a clue, I speak without a mouth and see without an eye, I bring the past, the present, and the future into view, What riddle am I?
A realm unseen, yet ever nigh.
A riddle I: I speak without a mouth and hear without ears. I have no body, but I come alive with the wind. What am I?
A rope.
A secret path leading nowhere, guarded by the brave and the bold, where treasures hidden lie, waiting to unfold.
A seven-letter word, the fewer letters I use of it, the more I convey, and that's how I make life sweet. What is it?
A shadow.
A shape that's full and round, But vanishes when it hits the ground.
A silent plea, often repeated, can bring a smile to any face. It's what the heart whispers when love is at stake.
A silent word, often misunderstood. It makes the poor rich and the rich poor. What am I?
A silent, hollow space, I am a place. Enter once, but leave with haste.
A single stir can fill a whole room, yet when empty, takes up none.
A single thread, yet holds the whole loom in tension.
A sleeping beauty in a stone, awakens with a gentle blow.
A symbol of knowledge, of wisdom wide.
A symbol of warmth and ever-welcome scene.

A tale of two sisters. Their love was vast and true. When one took a walk, the other watched over you. But in the end, they were to part, for one would stay, while the other would start a new journey. Which are the two sisters?
A teapot.
A thing comes from a mine, and its end is in fire. It begins in cold, and it never grows older. What is it?
A thing comes from an egg, is eaten, and after laying another egg, dies. What is it?
A thing comes in a pair and every man has two. We go out with our hats on and in with our coats off. What are they?
A thing created from three letters, silence is my song, with a voice I share, it brings both joy and gloom alone.
A thing made of nuts that is not a nut, what am I?
A thing of beauty, I'm shaved and used, I'm never empty, and I'm always refilled.
A thing of beauty, yet bright as the sun, When touched, it vanishes as if it had never begun. What is it?
A thing of beauty, yet it can bring great fear, it's always spinning, but it never moves from where it's placed.
A thing of great worth, I have no heart, No pulse, no life, no start. What am I?
A thing spoken with a heavy heart, A thing worn upon the outside, Which way I face, I neither move nor part, What am I?
A thing that grows in the night, Unseen by the moon's gentle light.
A thing that grows, but never gets old, Keeps time, but doesn't make any noise, It's always with me, and always in control, On every face, a part of the tale.
A thing that is always in a boat and yet never sails. What is it?
A thing that is always in front of me, but can't be seen or touched. You can live without it, but not for long. What is it?
A thing that is always in front of you but can't be seen or touched.
A thing that is always in the way. What it has to give us makes life worth living. What it is, we seldom see.
A thing that is always with you but can't be seen or touched, it starts ticking the moment you're born, what is it?
A thing that is beautiful to see and terrible to feel. What am I?
A thing that is bought by the foot, rolls when it's thrown, and costs twice as much when it's sent back?
A thing that is broken and can't be mended, yet by keeping it we seem to be friends. What is it?
A thing that is broken can't be what?
A thing that is light as a feather, yet even the strongest man cannot hold it for much longer than a minute. What is it?
A thing that is light, it is taken from the sea. In the mouth of a man, it is seldom pleasantry. What is it?
A thing that is light, yet heavy to hold. It travels east, then west, making the sun rise and set.
A thing that is lighted first thing in the morning and burnt at night.
A thing that is not alive, but grows; not living, but always grows.
A thing that is not alive, but still grows; it has roots above and leaves below. What is it?
A thing that is often broken but never falls. What am I?
A thing that is often broken, but never worn out. What am I?
A thing which gives light but continues burning, is not a candle, tell me what it is?
A thing you break, yet it's what you use to mend other things.
A thing you throw away that gets heavier the more you keep it. What is it?
A thing you throw away that grows every day, what is it?
A thousand may enter, but not a one may leave. What is it? A place where the young are never taken in, but the old cannot get out?
A three-letter word that starts with "e," contains one "e," and ends with two "e's." What is it?
A three-letter word that, when spoken twice, contains all the vowels used in the English language, as well as the second-highest number of consonants. What is it?
A three-letter word, silently you plead. Speak it and all is revealed.
A three-letter word, the first is a bird, the second is a fly, what is the third?
A three-letter word, two letters of which are in every English word. What is it?
A tiny seed, with the power to grow, When given the right conditions, it's a secret I'll show.
A treasure that can be found in a single grace.
A treasure that lies hidden in every place?
A voice within that helps you decide.
A wink, a nod, and a clandestine touch, stolen from a corner in the dark, what am I?
A woman was found dead in a field. She was lying on her back with her hands crossed in front of her. There were no signs of struggle. How did she die?
A woman's best friend, a man's worst fear. The more you have, the less you share.
A word I'm thinking of starts with an E, ends with an E, but only contains one letter. What is it?
A word made from four letters, Speaks of something both high and low, A sound that starts a gentle rain, A force that brings both pain and gain.
A word of five letters, remove two, and it's a creature you'll often find in the zoo.
A word of five letters, saying it will cost a penny, take a penny and in a pen it's written. What is it?
A word of five letters, spoken aloud is music, writ down is a command, what is it?
A word of four letters that becomes shorter when you add two letters to it. What is it?
A word of four letters, but when added a fifth, makes the first letter be worth twenty-five. What word is this?
A word of four letters, if you double its second, you'll name a color often found in a rainbow's arc.
A word of four letters, spoken after a curse, makes whatever follows doubly worse. What is it?
A word of four letters, spoken in anger, can never be unsaid.
A word of four letters, spoken silently, to which everyone listens closely.
A word of four letters, the first three letters I say, the fourth a holy man must pray.
A word of four letters, when added to the word 'bread', makes a sentence about bread that's long and round. What word is it?
A word of four letters, with but one letter changed, it spells delight, it makes the heart to wander, it's a lover's sweet refrain.
A word of six letters long. Take away three, and the remaining three will stand. What is it?
A word of six letters, take three away and what remains is worth eight? What is it?
A word of six letters, the last five are silence, the first is pain. What am I?
A word of three letters with one leg, that can't stand. What is it?
A word of three letters, if you add two, it still is one. What is this little word?
A word of three letters, said with a sigh, it's a feeling, I can't deny.
A word of three letters, spoken about wine, which when added to a glass will make it divine.
A word of three letters, spoken above, it means peace for those at home, but death for those at sea.
A word of three letters, spoken after "how," but on what do you always clown?
A word of three letters, spoken after a loss, spoken to a friend, which word?
A word of three letters, spoken after the rain. A sight that seldom is seen, a welcome sound again. What is it?
A word of three letters, spoken in the dark. Speak it, and no crowd will bark.
A word of three letters, spoken once a year, on the day dedicated to your dear. What word?
A word of three letters, spoken once, means "hello." Spoken twice, it means "goodbye." What is it?
A word of two letters, spoken softly, brings back a time long ago, a memory so dear in my mind to grow.
A word of two syllables, the last syllable taken from a monkey, the first from a bear. What am I?
A word spoken once and forgotten by a thousand, spoken a thousand times and hated by a few. What am I?
A word that begins with an E, ends with an E, but only contains one letter.
A word that describes a color that starts with an 'E', ends with an 'E', but only contains one letter. What is it?
A word that describes a colorless, odorless gas that fills the sky and makes us sneeze. What is it?
A word that is always in front of you but can't be seen.
A word that is pronounced the same forwards and backwards. What word is this?
A word that is spoken but never heard.
A word that makes a noise but doesn't let anything out. What am I?
A word that makes sense when spelled backwards. What is it?
A word that makes the whole world run around.
A word that means the beginning of decay, A color that means life has turned gray, Add ten letters, and it spells what we're afraid to say.
A word that means the opposite of itself.
A word that means the opposite of what it is.
A word that means the same as the first three letters, what is it?
A word that means to play a musical instrument, but you don't strum or pluck its strings.
A word that means to write with a pen, but the letters don't appear on paper. What is it?
A word that sounds like a bird, but when you add two letters, it means to shed a tear. What is it?
A word that sounds like water, but isn't a living thing, I can be in a cup or a jug, but also in a lake or a spring.
A word that starts with an E, ends with an E, but only contains one letter.
A word that's spoken, but can't be heard. Hidden in bushes, but can't be seen. What am I?
A word that, when you add two letters to it, changes it from a noun to a verb. What is the word?
A word used for a creature that is not alive, but once was.
A word uttered yet not spoken, a thing existed yet not there. What am I?
A word which is spelled forward but read backwards.
A word which is spoken too soon is a weed that kills the root of conversation. What is that word?
A word with five letters, taking all five, make a word meaning much when spelled backward. What is it?
A word with two letters that sounds like a dog barking.
A word, six letters long, in speech it brings a shout. Two letters changed, and it can make you frown.
An answer found within the simplest of prose.
An apple is cut into two, yet neither part is one. What's the term for that which is two?
An egg.
An empty box, six faces, no opening to be found. How many sides does it have?
An endless source of water that's never full, what am I?
An island of ice, with trees that burn, and houses made of glass. People wear furs, yet never feel the cold.
An object that's seen, but not touched, Often passed from hand to hand, Its value is measured in gold, silver, and grand. What object am I?
And drowns sorrow and cries without sound?
And in great books you'll find me in tens.
Answer to the bonus riddle: The woman was taking a bath, was holding the gun underwater to clean it, and was hanging the clothes to dry.
Answer: a pillow.
Answers I hold, but I give none away, I'm the enigma, the puzzle, the maze at the end of the day.
Around me at first you see darkness, but within me, a fire ignites.
Baked, but not in a pie's size.
Before it's baked, it's sour, after it's baked, it's sweet. What am I?
Before the first letter in a word, you'll always find me. What am I?
Beneath the Earth, or often in the sky, I'm a passage to another land, Where secrets are shared, and no one can deny, What am I?
Beneath the chin, I bring a smile. You can't hide and still be in my line.
Beneath the sea, I lie, in a castle grand, If you find me, you'll wish you didn't command.
Beneath the willow tree, three acorns lie. Two for the squirrel, one for the tree, how many are left for me?
Beware its sting, it hides in a shell, but for treasures hidden it gives you a tell.
Beware my power, for I can kill with a single touch. Yet, when I'm gone, all will rejoice and sing my praises. What am I?
Beware the deceiver, shrouded in night's sheet, With its silver tongue and a voice so sweet, It appears gentle, but hides cruel defeat, I am...
Beware the sunset's fiery glare, For it hides a formidable foe. My eyes can never see me, And my teeth are unending like the shore.
Bonus: A man had a large pond in his garden. It was reputed to be a mile around. He wanted to walk around it, but he could only walk one mile at a time. How did he manage it?
Born from the earth, I'm tall and green, my leaves are my food, my root is unseen. What am I?
Born from water, but not a fish, Easily hidden, yet always a dish, With branches that sway and grass that's rich, What object am I?
Born in a cauldron, yet pure as the morning's dew, a tiny creature that grows, yet it can't choose, where it wants to be, water or land.
Born in an ovary, hidden in a sheath, nourished by an umbilical thread, cut open and spread, what am I?
Born in despair, sought in happiness, I am taken from a mine, and shut up in a wooden case, from which I am never released, and yet I am used by almost every person.
Born in spring, and every autumn carried away?
Born in the winter, but not a snowman. Carried in the summer, but not for a picnic. What am I?
Born in water, whisked from the shore, if you've not tasted me, then you're a bore.
Born in winter, I grow in snow, I'm often used as a show. What am I?
Born not made, I grow on ground, what am I?

Born on a Monday, I grow red and bright, On a Tuesday, I'm cold and I bite, On a Wednesday, I swell up a treat, On Thursday, I'm slim and just a seat, On a Friday, I'm a sweet little treat, On Saturday, I'm all wrapped up neat, But on Sunday, I'm gone, out of sight. What am I?
Born out of fire and water, I'll bring your life to a close. What am I that you cannot ignore?
Bottled water.
Bridge: I have a body, but not organs. I have a head, but no brain. I have a bed, but no mattress. What am I?
Bright as a flame, hard as a diamond, clear as a crystal, I'm precious and rare, what am I?
Bringing joy and cheer to every belt.
But I can make your heart skip a beat.
But I vanish when the day is done.
But I'm used up and then thrown away.
But every day she shed a tear.
But the real me can't be undone.
But what I truly am, is rarely shown.
Can be cracked, made, told, and played, but to drink it, it must first be made?
Can you give me a word that becomes shorter when you add two letters to it?
Carved from a tree, I'm used to send messages, yet cannot speak.
Climbing higher, I touch the sky, A place where dreams and thoughts fly free, Transcending all that separates, I am the one who ties all states.
Colder than frozen ice, sharper than a razor's edge, quicker than the slightest sound, it's gone before you even touch around.
Creating a fearsome delusion.
Dozens: I am a word, say me, I come with six, subtract one and twelve is the fix.
Eaten by the young and old, it grows stronger with each tale. In the kitchen, on the table, it never goes stale.
Eggs in a basket and water in a sieve, Both hold their shapes, but one will surely grieve.
Eternal and ever-evolving, it's the whisper of chance, silent but powerful, it can shape the course of your life, what is it?
Five eyes I have and never shut, I see the world without any slut.
Footsteps.
Footsteps: The more you make, the more you leave behind.
Forged from water, yet clear.
Four ashes in hand make one spade.
Four legs in the morning, two at noon, three in the evening, how many at noon?
Four letters in words, first three letters in most, remove one letter and what remains is heard.
Four times a day, I'm whispered and sung, The moon, the noon, I am young, And when night comes, four times I cling.
From a mine I come, a fortune sought, Once broken, I can never be bought.
From all things I will take the last: I'll make the happiest man the last.
From east to west, from high to low, In silence, I help plants to grow, The seasons change as I wane, What am I?
From me, all poets and writers do reap.
From this point, all roads diverge. Choose one and change your fate.
From which I'm never released, and yet I'm often good.
Grows lighter as time and love depart.
Grows longer in winter and shorter in summer, and when it's gone, all is done.
